### Challenges Faced

```
Problem: psql command not found in Git Bash after installing PostgreSQL
Attempted solution: Reopened Git Bash expecting PATH to update automatically
Actual solution: Manually added PostgreSQL bin to PATH via export, then added to ~/.bashrc
Lesson learned: Windows PATH changes require manual export in Git Bash; ~/.bashrc persists it

Problem: RDS connection refused — security group blocking local IP
Attempted solution: Used curl ifconfig.me — returned IPv6 address, not recognized by AWS security group
Actual solution: IPv4 address (73.82.66.93) was what RDS saw; added that to inbound rule as /32 CIDR
Lesson learned: What your machine thinks its IP is and what AWS sees can differ; use the IP from the connection error, not ifconfig.me

Problem: verify-tag-audit.sh not finding untagged resources (zero-tag resources invisible to project filter)
Actual solution: Resolved independently
Lesson learned: Scripts that filter by project tag will never surface zero-tag resources — Lambda broad scan is the right tool for that
```

### What Worked Well

```
- Design session before writing any code — data model decisions made upfront saved significant rework
- Tagging console resources immediately after creation, before running any scripts
- Using Lambda test to verify tag audit before moving on
- cloud-governance-infra repo pattern — clean separation of shared vs project-specific infrastructure
```

